## Why Sayfa?

Sayfa is a static site generator built in Elixir. Unlike most SSGs that rely on Node.js, Sayfa runs entirely on the BEAM VM with Rust-powered Markdown rendering via MDEx. The result is a fast, reliable tool with a small dependency footprint.

What sets it apart:

- **No Node.js required** — TailwindCSS is handled via a standalone binary
- **Block system** — Reusable components without a JS framework
- **Built-in i18n** — 14 languages supported out of the box
- **5 content types** — Posts, notes, projects, talks, and pages

## Content Types

Sayfa organizes your content into types, each with its own directory and URL pattern:

| Type | Directory | URL | Best for |
|------|-----------|-----|----------|
| Posts | `content/posts/` | `/posts/slug/` | Blog articles, tutorials |
| Notes | `content/notes/` | `/notes/slug/` | Quick thoughts, TILs |
| Projects | `content/projects/` | `/projects/slug/` | Portfolio, showcases |
| Talks | `content/talks/` | `/talks/slug/` | Presentations, events |
| Pages | `content/pages/` | `/slug/` | About, contact, etc. |

Generate new content with the CLI:

```bash
mix sayfa.gen.content post "My New Post"
mix sayfa.gen.content note "Quick Tip"
mix sayfa.gen.content project "My App"
```

## Front Matter

Every content file starts with YAML front matter. Here's a complete example:

```yaml
---
title: "My Post Title"
date: 2024-01-15
updated: 2024-01-20
description: "A short description for SEO and social sharing"
categories: [guides, elixir]
tags: [tutorial, beginner]
featured: true
draft: false
image: /images/cover.jpg
layout: post
translations:
  tr: yazimin-basligi
---
```

Only `title` is required. Everything else is optional — Sayfa fills in sensible defaults.

## Writing Content

Sayfa uses MDEx for Markdown rendering, which supports GitHub Flavored Markdown with syntax highlighting built in.

### Code Blocks

Fenced code blocks get automatic syntax highlighting:

```elixir
defmodule MyApp.Greeter do
  @moduledoc "A simple greeter module."

  def hello(name) do
    name
    |> String.trim()
    |> then(&"Hello, #{&1}!")
  end
end
```

### Tables

Standard Markdown tables work:

| Feature | Status |
|---------|--------|
| Markdown | Done |
| Syntax Highlighting | Done |
| Dark Mode | Done |

